An address to a jar of wine, which Horace will broach in honor of his friend Corvinus.

Marcus Valerius Messala Corvinus was a student in Athens with Horace, and like him served in Brutus* army in 42 B.C.; later he took part in the struggle against Antony. He was consul in 31 B.C.‚ and in 27 B.C. enjoyed a triumph over the Aquitanians. After this he devoted himself to the practice of law and the pursuit and patronage of litera- ture. His eloquence is praised by Cicero (ad Brut. 1, 15, 1); Quin- tilian (10, 1, 113) compared his oratory with that of Asinus Pollio. Messala's great wealth and high socia] position made it possible for him to gather about him a literary circle second only to that of Maecenas. Tibullus was the most distinguished of this company, and has left many references in his verses to his patron.

The ode is dramatically conceived: the poet stands before the iars , stored in his apotheca and bids one contemporary with himself come down and yield up its store. whether it contain sport or contention As the gossip of tradition credits Messala with being a connoisseur oi wines, vv. 7— 10 possibly refer to his ability.
